Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE handlers (11006)
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE handlers run inside a MATCH's traversal. The
clause has three children: pattern (0), optional guard (1), body
(2). Pattern + guard lower to an expression yielding a Boolean;
the WHEN_CLAUSE child_exit emits the conditional branch from the
match value vs pattern result. Body lowers normally.

When clauses do not push their own frame — they peek the enclosing
MATCH frame to read match_value, current_arm_index, and the per-
arm labels.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
WHEN_CLAUSE pre is a no-op. WHEN_CLAUSE post is also a no-op
because MATCH's child_exit(i >= 1) handles the inter-arm wiring.
The child_enter/child_exit on the WHEN_CLAUSE itself fire per
child of the clause: pattern, guard (optional), body.

For child_exit(0=pattern): the pattern's MIR value is on top of
the result stack. Read the MATCH frame's match_value and the
current arm's case_label, emit a compare-eq, then branch to
case_label or next_label.

For child_exit(2=body): no-op (MATCH's child_exit(arm) handles
the jump-to-merge).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two emissions per arm (compare + branch).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Frame access bounded by peek.
@End Security_Scope

