Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_CATCH_CLAUSE handlers (11016)
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_CATCH_CLAUSE is a child of HIR_TRY_STATEMENT. The catch
clause's body is lowered as a normal block; the parent TRY's
child_exit handles the landingpad emission and exception-variable
mapping. The catch-clause handler itself is a no-op shell — it
exists so dispatch coverage is 100%. The HIR layer routes each
catch's body through the visitor in source order; the body's
statements emit normally inside the catch block established by
the parent TRY.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
pre/post: no-op. child_enter/child_exit: no-op.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Zero cost beyond the dispatch trampoline.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
No state mutation. The exception variable is mapped by the parent
TRY's child_exit handler; the catch clause does not re-map.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lower_hir_catch_clause_pre" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "lower_hir_catch_clause_child_enter" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer, child_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "lower_hir_catch_clause_child_exit" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer, child_index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "lower_hir_catch_clause_post" that takes ctx as Integer, hir_node_ptr as Integer, node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================
Note: HIR_FINALLY_CLAUSE handlers (11017)
Note: ============================================================

@Reasoning
HIR_FINALLY_CLAUSE post: lowers a finally-block. For the v0.0.8.5
pipeline, finally is implemented by inlining the finally-block's
MIR after both the try-body and each catch-body before the merge
label. The handler emits a finally-label marker so the
construction is identifiable, and a jump to the merge label after
the finally body emits its statements via the visitor recursion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
pre: allocate a finally_label, push it onto the frame stack under
a new kind (6 = FINALLY), emit the label marker.

child_enter/child_exit on the single body child: no-op (body
statements emit themselves).

post: peek frame, emit a jump to the enclosing TRY's merge_label
(if available via the frame chain), pop the FINALLY frame.

For v0.0.8.5 we cannot walk the frame chain past the top frame
without additional context bookkeeping. The handler emits only
the finally-label marker; the parent TRY is responsible for
recording the finally-body's emission position. When the parent
TRY's post runs, the merge-label is emitted; any straight-line
fallthrough from the finally body reaches the merge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two label/marker emissions per finally.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
A finally block without a matching TRY is structurally invalid;
the HIR layer rejects this before lowering.
@End Security_Scope

